 Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":1,\"like_count\":0,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@GemLeighton Those trees! They are leaning and talking about a forest fire happening a bit far away. The childish lines + the bleak colours! I love it.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-23T02:19:21.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":12,\"username\":\"GemLeighton\",\"id\":\"27779294\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384807422854848512\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384807422854848512\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1385415642048733188\",\"source\":\"Twitter Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":0,\"like_count\":0,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"My boss says I'm very meticulous and well-organised. Me glancing at my multiple Firefox windows full of tabs: \\\"lolwut? \\uD83E\\uDD23\\uD83D\\uDE02\\\"\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-23T02:10:03.000Z\",\"conversation_id\":\"1385415642048733188\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"20121920\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1385402215473442820\",\"source\":\"Twitter for iPhone\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":0,\"like_count\":0,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@Lazer Rule no. 1 of surviving in an Orwellian society: question *everything* *anybody* tries to make you believe, including “I love you”. \\uD83E\\uDD23\\uD83E\\uDD2A\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-23T01:16:42.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":6,\"username\":\"Lazer\",\"id\":\"20121920\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1385311016884609024\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1385311016884609024\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"7820042\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1385097314746781701\",\"source\":\"Twitter for iPhone\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":0,\"like_count\":0,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 This is just to say that you shouldn’t be surprised if some characters sound different in a song than in regular speech, because if the lyricist were worth any salt, they would have written in a way closer to poetry.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-22T05:05:08.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1385096769466363906\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"7820042\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1385096769466363906\",\"source\":\"Twitter for iPhone\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":1,\"like_count\":1,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 BTW, I forgot to remind you that many Chinese characters have multiple possible pronunciations, sometimes only differing in tone. And that depends on the context: character combinations, prose-vs-poetry, oral-vs-written, modern-vs-middle-age.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-22T05:02:58.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384735710620446720\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"7820042\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384777556969234434\",\"source\":\"Twitter Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":0,\"like_count\":1,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@WesleyCrasher @TimppaKarjalai1 However, even *I* cannot be of much help in understanding that article or book. I haven't actually learned much music theory. I'm just a software engineer whose mother tongue is Cantonese. And, officially, my Chinese level should be only about grade 4.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T07:54:32.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":14,\"username\":\"WesleyCrasher\",\"id\":\"942204136631816192\"},{\"start\":15,\"end\":31,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384776913369985032\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"942204136631816192\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384776913369985032\",\"source\":\"Twitter Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":1,\"like_count\":1,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@WesleyCrasher @TimppaKarjalai1 There's this article, which is about writing lyrics for Cantonese songs while taking the tones into account, from an experience lyricist's perspective: https://t.co/3vPbsHl2kE\\nThe article is probably just a quick summary of the book 《半步詞──由音樂劇到跨媒介的填詞進路》.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"entities\":{\"urls\":[{\"start\":184,\"end\":207,\"url\":\"https://t.co/3vPbsHl2kE\",\"expanded_url\":\"https://medium.com/%E8%AA%9E%E7%B5%B2%E8%AB%96%E5%8F%A2/%E9%AB%98%E4%BD%8E%E5%BD%B3%E4%BA%8D%E5%85%A8%E9%80%94%E4%B8%8A-%E4%B8%8A%E4%B8%8B%E5%BE%98%E5%BE%8A%E5%8D%8A%E6%AD%A5%E9%96%93-%E5%BE%9E-%E5%8D%8A%E6%AD%A5%E8%A9%9E-%E8%AB%96%E7%B2%B5%E8%AA%9E%E8%81%B2%E8%AA%BF%E6%9B%B2%E8%AA%BF%E4%BA%92%E5%8B%95%E4%BB%A5%E5%8F%8A%E7%B2%B5%E6%96%87%E5%89%8D%E6%99%AF-%E8%8F%AF%E6%96%87%E7%89%88-2c87bd6ad039\",\"display_url\":\"medium.com/%E8%AA%9E%E7%B…\"}],\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":14,\"username\":\"WesleyCrasher\",\"id\":\"942204136631816192\"},{\"start\":15,\"end\":31,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T07:51:58.000Z\",\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384762018637418497\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"7820042\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384735710620446720\",\"source\":\"Twitter for iPhone\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":2,\"like_count\":1,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 Which is also why I would suggest to avoid some of the more recent songs because some of the composers are brain-dead trained on Western musical theory and do not properly take Cantonese tones into account, and then we have crappy lyricists who write shitty lyrics on top.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T05:08:15.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384734667413151749\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"7820042\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384734667413151749\",\"source\":\"Twitter Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":2,\"like_count\":1,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 2. From a musical theory perspective, Chinese folk songs are mostly based on a subset of notes that aren't the same as, say, English folk song or Japanese folk song, exactly because they map better to certain tones. There's probably a book you can read about that.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T05:04:06.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384734120329191426\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"7820042\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384734120329191426\",\"source\":\"Twitter Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":2,\"like_count\":2,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 1. The note and the tone are not (always) directly related.\\nOften, you can express the correct tone through by correctly *varying* the audio frequency *within* the character syllable. It's the varying that matters, and the notes of the song are just adding frequency offsets.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T05:01:56.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384733747237441537\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"1340536122057904134\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384733747237441537\",\"source\":\"Twitter Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":1,\"like_count\":2,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 Yes, I realise the tonal property of languages such as Chinese can cause confusion. The really short answer that I would give has two parts.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T05:00:27.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384732009969471489\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"1340536122057904134\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384683754451394561\",\"source\":\"Twitter for iPhone\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":1,\"like_count\":1,\"quote_count\":1},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 Many oldies are slow paced and easy on the vocal chord, which makes them really good for practicing pronunciation. E.g. 「風繼續吹」，「倩女幽魂」，「滄海一聲笑」，etc. Too many to name.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T01:41:47.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384414105533128709\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384414105533128709\",\"lang\":\"ja\"},{\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1383823680103280642\",\"source\":\"Twitter