character combinations, prose-vs-poetry, oral-vs-written, modern-vs-middle-age.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-22T05:02:58.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384735710620446720\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"7820042\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384735710620446720\",\"source\":\"Twitter for iPhone\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":2,\"like_count\":1,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 Which is also why I would suggest to avoid some of the more recent songs because some of the composers are brain-dead trained on Western musical theory and do not properly take Cantonese tones into account, and then we have crappy lyricists who write shitty lyrics on top.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T05:08:15.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384734667413151749\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"942204136631816192\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384776913369985032\",\"source\":\"Twitter Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":1,\"like_count\":1,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@WesleyCrasher @TimppaKarjalai1 There's this article, which is about writing lyrics for Cantonese songs while taking the tones into account, from an experience lyricist's perspective: https://t.co/3vPbsHl2kE\\nThe article is probably just a quick summary of the book 《半步詞──由音樂劇到跨媒介的填詞進路》.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"entities\":{\"urls\":[{\"start\":184,\"end\":207,\"url\":\"https://t.co/3vPbsHl2kE\",\"expanded_url\":\"https://medium.com/%E8%AA%9E%E7%B5%B2%E8%AB%96%E5%8F%A2/%E9%A