pective, Chinese folk songs are mostly based on a subset of notes that aren't the same as, say, English folk song or Japanese folk song, exactly because they map better to certain tones. There's probably a book you can read about that.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T05:04:06.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384734120329191426\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"7820042\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384734120329191426\",\"source\":\"Twitter Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":2,\"like_count\":2,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 1. The note and the tone are not (always) directly related.\\nOften, you can express the correct tone through by correctly *varying* the audio frequency *within* the character syllable. It's the varying that matters, and the notes of the song are just adding frequency offsets.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T05:01:56.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384733747237441537\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"in_reply_to_user_id\":\"1340536122057904134\",\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384733747237441537\",\"source\":\"Twitter Web App\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":1,\"like_count\":2,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"@TimppaKarjalai1 Yes, I realise the tonal property of languages such as Chinese can cause confusion. The really short answer that I would give has two parts.\",\"author_id\":\"7820042\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T05:00:27.000Z\",\"entities\":{\"mentions\":[{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"username\":\"TimppaKarjalai1\",\"id\":\"1340536122057904134\"}]},\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"replied_to\",\"id\":\"1384732009969471489\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"source\":\"Twitter for Android\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":1,\"like_count\":0,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"I've asked lots of canto speakers how do they sing in note and in right tone simultaneously and I got a bunch of different answers. One of them was \\\"it doesn't matter in a song\\\" - a HK girl and a canto native speaker told me that lolz https://t.co/NFaeMd1iNN\",\"author_id\":\"1340536122057904134\",\"entities\":{\"urls\":[{\"start\":235,\"end\":258,\"url\":\"https://t.co/NFaeMd1iNN\",\"expanded_url\":\"https://twitter.com/k_sze/status/1384683754451394561\",\"display_url\":\"twitter.com/k_sze/status/1…\"}]},\"created_at\":\"2021-04-21T04:53:32.000Z\",\"referenced_tweets\":[{\"type\":\"quoted\",\"id\":\"1384683754451394561\"}],\"conversation_id\":\"1384732009969471489\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"entities\":{\"annotations\":[{\"start\":20,\"end\":39,\"probability\":0.6406,\"type\":\"Other\",\"normalized_text\":\"Chinese Language Day\"},{\"start\":98,\"end\":104,\"probability\":0.6836,\"type\":\"Product\",\"normalized_text\":\"Spotify\"}]},\"possibly_sensitive\":false,\"id\":\"1384414105533128709\",\"source\":\"Twitter for Android\",\"public_metrics\":{\"retweet_count\":0,\"reply_count\":3,\"like_count\":6,\"quote_count\":0},\"text\":\"Today is apparently Chinese Language Day or something. I'm listening to old Grasshopper record on Spotify and thinking how the heck did I manage not learning at least basic Cantonese in 20+ years listening to cantopop and watching HK movies? Bad Timppa\",\"author_id\":\"1340536122057904134\",\"created_at\":\"2021-04-20T07:50:18.000Z\",\"conversation_id\":\"1384414105533128709\",\"lang\":\"en\"},{\"entities\":{\"annotations\":[{\"start\":39,\"end\":40,\"probability\":0.5242,\"type